<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-092-069 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 303 135</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  August 1991 v31 n8 p36(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer classrooms in higher education: an innovation inteaching.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kettinger, William J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computers offer a new dimension in teaching, but little isactually known about their use in the US.andP;  Early use in highereducation seemed limited to requiring students to turn in computerprintouts to verify completion of their assignments.andP;  The computeris now becoming an active teaching tool in the classroom.andO;Computers are used as presentation systems, structuredlaboratories, modified lecture tools, and in self-pacedclassrooms.andP;  The most beneficial application of computertechnology seems to be in simulations that cannot be created in atraditional laboratory environment.andP;  The high costs and resistanceby teachers have retarded acceptance of the computer in theclassroom, but the computer will ultimately prove to be a valuableaddition to the teaching arsenal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationTeachingComputer-Assisted InstructionComputer-Managed InstructionSimulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>